shared_text:
MWP After School Program
August 13 at 11:13 AM ·

MWP After School Fall Program will start Sept. 7th and run through Oct. 16th. This fall we will be doing Positive Action and 4-H Cooking!!! This session will be from the comfort of your home with food delivery or pick up options weekly. There will be short video lessons posted here on the page that you/your kids will watch each week. This will also be the hub for posting pictures of the recipes and final products your student makes! We will be providing one meal per child per week based on the donations we receive. Registration forms can be found at the post offices in Morton, Glenoma, and Randle, or at the Morton Police Department. We will be able to accept 20 students from White Pass and 20 from Morton. Registration forms will be due August 31st.

Today's Morton senior is Hailee Erskine
My favorite teacher during my time at Morton High School? Mrs. Hanger
Best advice your parents/teachers have given you? No matter what life throws at you always keep your head up and keep moving forward.
Television marathon I could watch all day? Supernatural
My favorite subject in school? Weightlifting
Biggest challenge in school? Showing up
City or country I’d like to visit? Australia
Most famous celebrity I’ve seen in person? Brandy Clark
If I had to cook all of my meals, I'd survive on mac and cheese and cheeseburgers.
Furthest I’ve been from Washington? El Paso, Texas
Superpower I’d like to have? Teleport
Favorite thing to do on a lazy day? Sleep and eat
Thing(s) I’m most thankful for? I am most thankful for my family and friends that have supported me and have always been there for me.
Childhood ambition? When I was little I wanted to be a doctor, then I wanted to be a vet.
In ten years, I will be working at a vet’s office, married and a long way from Morton.

post_text: All 31 Morton graduations will take place this week beginning Thursday (June 4) afternoon. Each of the graduations will be five to 10-minute personal ceremonies at each of the graduate's houses (some graduations will have multiple graduates) with Superintendent John Hannah, a school board member, and the families of the graduates. There will be four graduation stops on Thursday, eight on Friday and the rest on Saturday.

post_text:
Today's Morton senior is Hayden Young.
I plan to attend Central Washington University to get a degree in construction management or business. After that I hope to have a career in whichever I choose.
My favorite teachers have been Mr. Dayton, even though he is a Chiefs’ fan, and Ms. West.
The best advice I have gotten is if you really want something work hard for it.
A marathon I could watch on tv is re-runs of college basketball games.
My favorite subject in school is weights and English.
My biggest challenge in school was doing homework on time.
I would travel to New York and LA.
The most famous celebrity I’ve been in person is Bill Belichick or Khalid.
If I had to cook all my meals I would survive off most anything; I am a really good chef.
If I could have a superpower it would be to duplicate myself, so I could multitask easier.
My lazy day is watching tv and playing some video games.
I’m thankful for all the opportunities that I get.
My childhood ambition was to be an NFL Star.
In 10 years, I will be a happy man.

Thank you for helping!!

post_text:
Today's Morton senior is Landen Kemp

Plans after graduation? I want to better myself physically and mentally.
My favorite subjects in school? History and creative writing.
Biggest challenge? Finding the motivation for just about anything.
The talent I’d most like to have? Dancing. Because having all the moves in all the right places can take you farther than you might expect.
The countries I would like to visit would be Guam, Germany, and Scotland. I've heard the views are breathtaking.
Furthest I’ve been from Washington? I went to Washington D.C and had a blast, although it was a little too hot there for my taste.
My Superpower? Flawless memory and comprehension. Never having to write down notes or take pictures and being able to completely recall anything I’ve seen or heard has too many benefits to even think about listing.
Favorite thing to do on a lazy day? Sleep, read, laugh at dumb stuff the internet. Pretty standard.
Childhood ambition? I wanted to be a breakdancer.

post_text: Reminder: Beginning Monday, March 23rd, the Morton School District will begin providing breakfast and lunch for all children in our district ages 0-18. These meals will be delivered curb side even if your child is not on our normal bus routes; Morton area delivery will be approximately 9:00 am and Mineral will be approximately 9:25 am Children must be present at the time of meal drop off. The meals are free of charge to all 0-18 year olds in our district. Please fill out the survey at shorturl.at/inQW1 if you are going to sign up for meal service for your child/ren. Also, child care to students whose parents/guardians work in the medical field or are first responders begins on Monday, March 23rd. Please fill out the survey at shorturl.at/orxU5 if you qualify for child care from the district. Both food service and child care links can also be found on our website at the top of the page.

Public Service Announcement
DATE: March 12th, 2020
RE: Follow-up to Gov. Inslee’s Message
TO: Morton School District Staff, Students, and Community Members
Today at 2:00 PM Governor Inslee announced a directive to close K-12 schools in King, Pierce, and Snohomish counties
from March 16th through April 24th. Districts in these counties can continue to provide food services, instructional programs (not in large group settings), and are asked to provide child-care services to health care and first responders.
Morton School District, Lewis County, and the rest of the state will continue to be monitored as this decision may grow over time to affect others. The decision will be based on the spread of the virus and the rates of confirmed cases.

CHRONLINE.COM
Mock Trial, Real Court: Morton Students Hone Their Skills in Lewis County Superior Court

Peter Abbarno
January 29 at 8:05 PM ·

Very honored to support and volunteer with the Morton School District students and their teacher Amanda West. This is a great program and group of students worth supporting.

"Participation in the team both teaches students how the law and justice system works and could inspire a student to pursue a career related to the justice system, he said. It also teaches them to work together, and Peter Abbarno said he can see it improve the students’ confidence throughout the year."

If you are interesting in supporting the Washington State YMCA Youth & Government program and these great students (and future leaders), please consider sending donations to Morton School District, Attn: Mock Trial Team, 152 Westlake Ave, Morton, WA 98356.

post_text:
Morton alum and former Morton/White Pass Timberwolves’ standout Zach Walton currently plays for the Drexel Dragons in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. They will be playing their first Colonial Athletic Association road contest of the year this evening. The Dragons tip-off at 6 p.m. against Towson in a nationally-televised game on the CBS Sports Network (3 p.m. on the west coast).
Drexel is now 9-7 overall and 2-1 in CAA play. The Dragons just completed a three-game homestand, where they defeated UNCW and Delaware after opening the stretch with a loss to Charleston. Zach Spiker's team has now won four of its last five games. Walton, a 6-6 senior, is averaging 12.2 points per game, shooting 41 percent from the field and 77 percent at the foul line. He scored a career-best 32 points earlier this season vs. Bryant.
Anyone interested can join a group of fans at the Moose Lodge in Morton to watch the game.
(photo courtesy of the Drexel Athletic Dept.)

post_text: The 9th annual Morton Elementary food drive collected 2,660 items and weighed 1,166.5 lbs. This year's food drive bested the 2018 food drive by 981 items and 140 lbs. All items were donated to Pastor's Pantry in Morton. This year’s student leaders were Julie Crittenden - 5th grade (front left), Vernon Richards - 5th grade (front right), Karah Fairhart - 6th grade (back left), and Aiden Kampa - 6th grade (back right).

Please take a moment to support the Morton UP! Coalition.
Simply spending a few minutes of your time and sharing your perspective is a valuable contribution.
Annually, at this time of year, the Morton UP! Coalition asks community members to support the coalition by completing a survey. The survey captures individual perspectives on the availability of drugs and alcohol in the community. You can help support the coalition by completing a survey electronically. Your assistance and feedback is appreciated! Hard copy surveys are also available upon request by calling 360-740-1424. Please complete a survey by Sunday, December 15, 2019. Thank you!
Morton UP! Community Survey Link:
https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/LEMO2019EN

The Morton Jr. High ASB will be sponsoring a fundraising sale. All the money generated through this fundraising drive will go towards rewards and activities. Your participation in this sale, whether large or small, will have a real impact. Please take a look at the Winter Wonderland catalog and share it with families and friends. The start date is September 23 and it will run until October 4.
To order online please go to supportmyschool.org. Click "register" and the seller ID for Morton JH is # 967137.
Never allow students to solicit orders alone. They should always be in the company of an adult. Personal checks, bank checks, and money orders must be made out to Morton School. No cash for orders, please.

post_text: Earlier today, The Morton Jr./Sr. High School building received a threat and went into lock-down. Staff and law enforcement reacted very quickly to ensure the safety of our students and staff. Because of the quick response, all students and staff were safe.
text: Earlier today, The Morton Jr./Sr. High School building received a threat and went into lock-down. Staff and law enforcement reacted very quickly to ensure the safety of our students and staff. Because of the quick response, all students and staff were safe.

post_text: Today during lunch we went into lockdown over a threat made. The students and building were secured quickly and law enforcement was on scene immediately. The police have spoken to the person who made the threat and we are following-up with the family.

post_text:
Congratulations to the 12 Morton/White Pass athletes that competed in the State 2B Track Meet at Eastern Washington University in Cheney.
Seniors Tristan Storey, Jesse Urban, Kaleb Rashoff and junior Manuel Martinez won the 400-relay in 43.84, just four-tenths of a second off the meet record. Storey also placed second in both the 100 (11.50 in final - 11.07/PR in prelims) and 200 (22.58/PR in final). Rashoff finished seventh in the long jump (19-9½), 10th in the 300 hurdles (43.25), and senior Gavyn Higdon was eighth in the javelin (157-9). The Morton/White Pass boys placed seventh in the state with 29 points of the 55 teams represented.
Seniors Elexcious Hampton, Ashley Wurtz, Jacie Dunlap and freshman Jordan Koetje finished 13th in the girls' 800-relay (1:54.50). Dunlap also placed 14th in the 300 hurdles (51.64/PR) and Koetje 16th in the 100 (14.65). Senior Emily Elswick placed 12th in the discus (92-7) as did sophomore Katie Salguero in the shot (30-8¾), and senior Kaylen Collette was 13th in the 3200 (13:16).

post_text:
Color Bowl Planting
The Morton FFA Chapter will be hosting a Color Bowl Planting night just in time for Mother's Day. The planting night will be held on Monday, May 6, from 5-7:30 pm.
FFA will provide all materials needed as well as light refreshments, so simply come and plant a Color Bowl! Quantity available will depend on amount pre-sold. These will be 14" bowls containing petunias, lobelia, and marigolds.
If you are interested in reserving a Color Bowl you may ask one of the FFA officers, or contact Mrs. Hanger at Morton High School. Color bowls planted at the event must be taken home by the end of the day Tuesday, May 7.
Single color bowls are $18 or buy two for $30. Color bowls must be pre-ordered. Please make checks payable to Morton High School ASB.
If you have questions please contact Mrs. Hanger at the high school (360.496.5137).
Thank you for supporting the Morton FFA Chapter!

post_text: Thank you to all of the volunteers of Lewis County Fire District #4 in Morton who hosted a Fire Safety Day last week at the elementary school for Fire Prevention Week. The students were given a tour of the fire truck with all of its bells and whistles, and visited stations in the gym providing information about fire safety. All the students received fire safety bags, the third graders received smoke alarms, and the fourth graders received new batteries for the alarms they received last year.

The Timberwolves' football team (5-2 overall, 1-2 league) hits the road to play the 8th-ranked Rainier Mountaineers (5-2, 1-2) tonight at 7 p.m.
“We’re both tied for fourth in the league, and basically the loser is staying home from the playoffs this year,” Coach Lee Metcalf said. “Last year it as a 41-40 game at their place in a game we thought we could have won. They’re better this year and we’re better this year so we’ll see how it goes. We’re going to give it our best and hopefully, we’ll come out with a victory.”

post_text: The Morton/White Pass Timberwolves, in their 10th year as a combination, will host the Neah Bay Red Devils today at 2 p.m. in Morton. Fans are encouraged to bring lawn chairs for additional seating around the track. The contest will be unique in the fact that Neah Bay is a 1B school and plays eight-man football. For this game, when the Red Devils have the ball each team will play with eight players, but when Morton/ White Pass is on offense they will play 11-on-11. The game with Neah Bay will be the 101st in team history and will be the first game in Morton since the T-Wolves beat Pe Ell 46-0 on September 14, 2012.
